      {
        "id": 4096761,
        "name": "J0$hua Levin$0n",
        "username": "J.Levinson",
        "avatar_template": "/letter_avatar_proxy/v4/letter/j/a587f6/{size}.png",
        "created_at": "2023-06-19T04:55:35.217Z",
        "cooked": "<p>At least you\u2019re not looking for 2002 <img src=\"https://www.wineberserkers.com/images/emoji/unicode/sweat_smile.png?v=12\" title=\":sweat_smile:\" class=\"emoji\" alt=\":sweat_smile:\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"20\" height=\"20\">!</p>\n<p>I\u2019d say most Brunelleschi are probably fine, especially the usual suspects (Biondi Santi, Soldera) if you find them. They\u2019re likely peaked now and not something you want to take back to age.</p>\n<p>Another option would be a vin santo from 2003. Some of the smaller producers make some great vin santo since the longer process means it\u2019s often made more out of love than for profit.</p>",
        "post_number": 2,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 9,
